Mounted of an Orange-wattled Kokako, a now extinct species of bird.
NarNarrative: Yesterday a Gal?pagos tortoise called Lonesome George died. With him died his entire race. George was the last of his kind - the last tortoise from Pinta Island. The bird below is an orange wattled Kokako from our collection. Once found on New Zealand's South Island, it's now extinct. Kokakos on the North Island survive, but their wattles are blue, not orange. The species survives, but the orange wattled birds are gone - and like Lonesome George, we'll never see their like again. Here's some footage of poor old George; http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CzRLt4ivtVk&feature=related

NarNarrative: This Bewick's Swan was discovered at Haydon Bridge, Northumberland, by Richard Wingate of Newcastle upon Tyne. It was the second of its kind to be found, and was described in 1830 as a new species of animal, called Bewick's Swan (Cygnus bewickii), in honour of Thomas Bewick. It is a type specimen of that species. There was controversy between several ornithologists who claimed to be the first to see this species but the first person to publish a description was W. Yarrell, shortly beating P.J. Selby.
LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Haydon Bridge

NarNarrative: The Red Breasted Goose is a small goose that breeds in parts of northern Siberia, and migrates south to spend the winter around the coast of the Black Sea in Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania. A few birds reach western Europe each winter. This specimen is believed to be the first bird ever recorded in Britain, shot near London in the winter of 1776. There have been about 60 records of the bird since then, mainly in the south east.

It is found in open areas near water and marshes and is frequently seen on farmland. Some farmers use them as guards as they are very aggressive and give out a loud call when disturbed. ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Chough
NarNarrative: The chough is a member of the crow family, but is almost exclusively a resident of rocky environments. For this reason it is generally confined to mountainous areas or high sea cliffs. In Britain its found mainly in the Hebrides and along the welsh coast. It forages for soil invertebrates on short grazed turf and often lives in association with livestock. When the grass is allowed to grow taller the chough can't reach the soil and so has difficulty feeding

Mount of a New Zealand Fruit Pigeon
NarNarrative: The New Zealand Fruit Pigeon is a relatively common species in New Zealand, where it feeds on the fruits of native trees. After Europeans colonised New Zealand, numbers declined, but the pigeon has recovered since then. This successful recovery is probably due to the complete ban on hunting that has existed since 1921.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Top-knot Pigeon
NarNarrative: The Topknot pigeon is a large pigeon with a uniquely shaped crest making it identifiable from a distance. Both males and females have the crest, which is rusty brown on the back of the head and grey on the forehead. Topknot pigeons are found in the rainforests of eastern Australia, where they live in flocks high up in the canopy, feeding on fruit. These pigeons are nomadic and may fly great distances in search of food.

NarNarrative: The Sacred Kingfisher is common throughout the coastal regions of mainland Australia and is also found on islands across Australasia from Indonesia to New Zealand. It lives in forests and mangrove swamps. In Australia, Sacred Kingfishers spend the winter in the north and fly south in the spring to breed. Unlike European kingfishers, Sacred Kingfishers forage mainly on land, only occasionally hunting in the water. They feed mainly on crustaceans, reptiles and insects.

Mount of a Homing Pigeon
NarNarrative: Homing pigeons possess the ability to find their way back home from a strange location, often over hundreds of miles. No-one knows exactly how they do this. The pigeons have tiny magnetic particles in their brains and can sense the planet's magnetic field. They may be able to use this sense to find the right direction to fly in. They are also known to navigate using visual landmarks such as roads and the position of the sun in the sky.

Mount of a Red-necked Nightjar
NarNarrative: This is the first recorded British specimen of a Red-necked Nightjar, and a rare record from northern Europe. This Red-necked Nightjar was shot at Killingworth in Northumberland on 5 October 1856 and was purchased by John Hancock from a gamedealer called Pape the next day. Red-necked nightjars hunt for moths during the night. Their feathers are patterned to look like dead leaves. This helps to hide them while resting on the ground or perching on branches during the day.

Mount of a Jackdaw
NarNarrative: The jackdaw is a small crow that is common throughout the British Isles, in both urban and rural areas. Jackdaws nest in small colonies of 20 or 30, normally in stands of tall trees. Like all members of the crow family, they will steal the eggs and chicks from other birds' nests during the breeding season. In some inner city areas, they survive almost exclusively on a diet of pigeon eggs and young chicks.

Mount of a Red-ruffed Fruit Crow
NarNarrative: The Red Ruffed Fruit Crow, or Indian Crow, comes from South America where it is widespread across the Amazon basin and much of Brazil. The bright red breast area contains about 300 red-tipped feathers - these have been exported and used to make flies for salmon fishing for over 150 years. This trade has resulted in the crow becoming rare in parts of its range, and it is now under protection. Today artificial feathers are used to make the flies.

NarNarrative: The Northern Flicker is a medium sized woodpecker found throughout North America. Unusually, the Northern Flicker is unable to hammer holes in solid wood. Instead these birds pry apart soft, rotting wood in search of insects. This specimen belongs to the eastern race of the species, which is also known as the Yellow Shafted Flicker. It ranges from Northern Canada as far south as Central America, and from the East Coast of the USA to the Rocky Mountains.

NarNarrative: The starling is one of the most familiar of garden birds, and is a common sight across much of Northern Europe and Russia, stretching from Spain as far north as Iceland. One of the most remarkable aspects of the Starling's behaviour is its ability to mimic sounds and incorporate them into their song - mainly the calls of other birds but also other animals and even mechanical noises. Starlings have been known to imitate car alarms and telephones whilst singing.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a White-chinned Petrel, on a cork base.
NarNarrative: The white chinned petrel is a large seabird found throughout the Southern Hemisphere. The birds are powerful flyers and wander many thousands of miles across the oceans. They breed on islands in the Southern Ocean with the largest colonies nesting on South Georgia. They frequently follow fishing boats in search of food, and this makes them vulnerable to becoming ensnared in nets and lines and drowning. Many thousands die this way every year and the population is beginning to decline.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Great-crested Grebe
NarNarrative: The chicks of the Great Crested Grebe are precocial. This means that shortly after hatching they are independent - the chicks can swim and dive like the adults. Whilst the chicks are small, the adults often carry them on their backs as they swim around. As the chicks grow larger, they begin to take on a more adult appearance and lose their distinctive black and white striped plumage.

Mount of a Green Woodpecker on a branch
NarNarrative: The Green Woodpecker is a large and distinctive species native to most of Europe and as far east as Iran. It lives in lowland forests, mainly in mature trees. Like most woodpeckers, it feeds on insect larvae by pecking holes in dead trees with its powerful bill. It is very secretive and is more often heard than seen. It has a high pitched laughing call which has led to it being called the Yaffle in some areas.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Hummingbird
Mount of a Hummingbird
Mount of a Great-crested Grebe
NarNarrative: Although it is now widespread, the Great Crested Grebe was once a rare bird. The 19th Century fashion for feather hats led to the large scale slaughter of thousands of grebes across Europe. In 1860 there were just 42 breeding pairs left in England. However since protection was imposed shortly after this the British grebe population has been recovering, and is now several thousand breeding pairs.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Wren
Mount of a House Sparrow
NarNarrative: This house sparrow is an almost complete albino - it has pure white feathers and pale coloured legs and beak. The eyes would have been pink, but were replaced with black glass eyes when the bird was stuffed. Complete albino birds are extremely rare in the wild, because their colouration makes them highly visible to predators.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Hoopoe
NarNarrative: The hoopoe is a brightly coloured and highly distinctive bird native to most of Europe, Africa, the Middle East and Asia as far east as India. It's a common sight in and around towns and cities throughout much of this area, often nesting in gardens. In Britain it's a rare visitor but has been known to breed here in the past. Normally the large crest is held flat against its head, but it is erected whenever the bird is alarmed.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Superb Starling
NarNarrative: The Superb Starling is a common bird throughout North East Africa, where it forms large flocks. It is often seen around towns and cities, and lives in a variety of different habitats. Like the more familiar Eurasian Starling the Superb Starling is a very good mimic, and it often imitates the calls of other birds in its song

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenshank
Mount of a Common Tern
NarNarrative: A common sight in summer, Common terns return from their wintering grounds in Africa every year to breed. They often nest together in large colonies, which may contain several hundred to several thousand birds. The common tern feeds by skimming the water surface as it flies or striking the water in shallow dives. It feeds on small fish and occasionally shrimp or aquatic insects are taken. They migrate back to Africa for the winter, leaving around October every year

Mount of a Black-necked Grebe
NarNarrative: The Black Necked Grebe is found throughout Europe and Asia. It lives in small and heavily vegetated lakes and ponds. Unlike most grebes, it prefers to feed on insects and molluscs rather than fish and so tends to feed from the water surface rather than diving. In Britain it breeds only in a few isolated areas, but many Black Necked Grebes spend the winter on the sea off the coast of southern and eastern England.

NarNarrative: The Corncrake is a medium sized rail that breeds in meadows and cereal fields. It was previously very widespread across most of Europe, but numbers have declined dramatically over the past century. Modern agriculture, in particular mechanised harvesting and mowing, destroys nests and often kills the chicks and young birds before they can escape. In Britain Corncrakes are now only found in the far north of Scotland, where conservation efforts are underway to try and reverse the decline.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Purple Gallinule
NarNarrative: The Purple Gallinule is the largest rail in Europe, and its bright colours make it an unmistakable bird. In Europe it lives in a few scattered coastal marshes and estuaries, mainly in Spain and the Balearic Islands where populations are threatened by hunting. It is generally very secretive and rarely emerges from dense cover. Its very large toes allow it to climb vertically up the stems of reeds and to walk across the water surface on lilly pads.

The male defends a small territory and can often be seen singing from a vantage point, normally a tree or bush. This bird has an extremely large upper mandible to it's bill, probably due to a genetic abnormality.

Birds like blackbirds or crows are often seen with patches of white feathers that would perhaps go un-noticed on other birds. However, the striking white patches on this bird's head and chest make it highly conspicuous.

Recently its range has been expanding northwards. This is partly due to deforestation, which is creating new grassy habitats where there was once rainforest.

As its name suggests, it feeds on bees and wasps, but will also take a variety of insects as food. It digs a burrow in a sandy bank, and will often nest colonially. It is a very rare visitor to Britain, but one or two are normally seen here every year.

NarNarrative: The blue cheeked Bee-eater is a colourful bird that breeds in arid regions of the Middle East and Asia and migrates to sub-Saharan Africa for the winter. It feeds mainly on wasps, ants and bees, hence its name. It nests by digging a burrow in a sandy bank, and birds often form colonies of several hundred burrows in parts of the Middle East. In some areas, where suitable nesting sites are unavailable, it will even burrow into the ground.

NarNarrative: The white feathers of this bird are due to albinism. This is a genetic condition in which the bird lacks a pigment, melanin, which normally gives a dark colour to its skin and feathers. This bird is a partial albino - only some of the feathers are affected, with some areas remaining black. Partial albinism occurs in most bird species, but true albinos, which are completely white with pink skin and eyes, are very rare in the wild.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Lapwing
NarNarrative: The Lapwing, (shown here in summer plumage) is also known as the Peewit due to its distinctive call and is widespread across Europe and Asia. It prefers open, flat habitats with short vegetation. As agriculture encroached on the Lapwing's traditional habitat, it managed to adapt to living on farm fields and became a relatively common breeding bird in many areas. However, like many farmland birds it has declined in number over recent years, and is the focus of conservation efforts.

Mount of a Great Grey Shrike
NarNarrative: The Great Grey Shrike is a predatory bird that feeds on large insects, small birds and rodents. They don't have sharp talons, but instead carry their unfortunate prey to a nearby bush and impale it on a sharp thorn or twig to kill it. This rather gruesome habit has given the Great Grey Shrike the colloquial name 'Butcher Bird'. It's an uncommon visitor to Britain. A few of these birds spend the winter in parts of the south.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Great Grey Shrike
NarNarrative: This species has until recently been regarded as a subspecies of the Great Grey Shrike. However, ornithologists recently decided that it was a separate species. This is because, as well as slightly different colouration, it is found only in southern regions of Europe and parts of the Middle East, and is very rarely seen further north. It also prefers dryer and more desert-like environments to the Great Grey Shrike.

Mount of a Game Cock
NarNarrative: Gamecocks are breeds of chicken traditionally bred for cockfighting. This involves pitting pairs of cockerels against each other, and betting on the outcome of the fight. The birds' spurs are often cut off and replaced with steel blades, or in this specimen, sharpened metal spikes called gaffes. These inflict severe wounds, killing or severely injuring the losing bird. Cockfighting was banned in the UK in 1952, but unfortunately the practice still continues illegally in some areas.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Game Cock
NarNarrative: In traditional English cockfighting, the birds' feathers were clipped to give them a streamlined appearance and make it harder for opponents to grab on to the feathers with their beaks. The comb and wattles on the cockerels' heads were also cut off for this reason. Where cockfighting is still popular, like the Philippines, the birds' feathers are generally left intact. However, in order to improve performance, drugs are often given to the cockerels to make them faster and more aggressive.

NarNarrative: Snowy owls live in the tundra regions north of the tree-line. They breed in the far north, but move southwards in the winter. Like most owls, they are mainly active at twilight, but in the land of the midnight sun they have no choice other than to hunt in daylight. Snowy owls feed on Lemmings, and in a poor Lemming year the population of owls will crash.

Mount of a Honey Buzzard
NarNarrative: The Honey Buzzard lives in mature woodland, and is a very rare visitor to Britain. A few pairs breed here every year. It takes its name from its main food source - wasps and bees. The Honey Buzzard will follow one back to its nest, and will then attack the nest, feeding on the grubs and honey inside. The small scaly head feathers help to protect it from stings. It may also have some immunity to the insect venom.

The identification is made a little difficult because the beak and legs appear to have been painted yellow, but the bird appears to be either a Gray-headed or possibly a Buller's Albatross. Albatrosses are southern-hemisphere birds, the South American coasts having more species than anywhere else.

Mount of a Greenland Falcon
Mount of a Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: As with most birds of prey, the female Gyrfalcon is the larger and heavier bird. A male normally weighs about 2.5 lbs (just over 1kg), whereas the female normally weighs about 3.5 lbs (about 1.6kg). The birds form a pair bond that lasts until one of the pair dies. In bad years when there is less food, Gyrfalcons will not breed. On average they manage to breed in three out of every five years. The female normally incubates the eggs.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: Gyrfalcons occur in a range of differently coloured 'morphs', depending on their chosen habitat. The darkest coloured birds live at the southern limit of the species natural range, where their dark grey plumage camouflages them against rocks and tundra. The birds become paler in colour further to the north. Birds in Greenland, at the northern limit of the species' range, can be almost pure white in colour, which camouflages them against the snow and ice.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Gyrfalcon, Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: The Gyrfalcon prefers to nest on cliff faces, often on a ledge beneath an overhang to protect its eggs from bad weather. It doesn't make a nest, preferring to use a scrape - a shallow depression perhaps lined with a few twigs. Four eggs are normally laid, and take just over a month to hatch. After hatching the chicks take about seven weeks until they can fly. They remain dependant on their parents for food for several weeks after this.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Gyrfalcon, Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: Gyrfalcons lay their eggs in spring, as the cold weather is beginning to change. The eggs are incubated for about a month. The chicks are downy and helpless immediately after hatching, but learn to feed themselves within a month. They normally leave the nest within another 20 days. Their parents still bring them food whilst they acquire hunting skills, but they become fully independent within another month. The chicks have to mature quickly, before the cold northern winter takes hold.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Gyrfalcon, Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: Gyrfalcons live in the arctic and sub-arctic regions of Europe, Asia and America. The most northerly populations migrate south in the autumn as the snowline advances, but are never normally found further south than the northern USA or central Russia. However, single birds are occasionally recorded further south in parts of Europe and Asia. These birds have normally become disoriented whilst on migration. Gyrfalcons are occasionally recorded in the British Isles.

Mount of a Spanish Imperial Eagle, Adalbert's Eagle
NarNarrative: This small eagle is now only found in parts of Spain. It was once also found in Algeria and Morocco, but has now become extinct there. It is a critically endangered species. There are two remaining strongholds - the Extremadura region in western Spain, and the Coto Donana national park in Andalucia. This bird is an adult male, and was shot in what is now Coto Donana national park in 1883. It was donated to the Hancock museum in 1929.
SciName: Aquila adalberti : Accipitridae : Falconiformes : Aves : Chordata

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Spanish Imperial Eagle
NarNarrative: Young Spanish Imperial Eagles leave the nest after two or three months. Juveniles are easily identified by their pale colouring. They don't develop full adult plumage until 4 or 5 years old. Juvenile survival is often quite low, with few birds living longer than a few years after leaving the nest. The eagles naturally seek out vantage points from which they can look for their preferred prey, rabbits. Unfortunately these young birds often perch on overhead wires and are electrocuted.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: The Gyrfalcon is the world's largest species of Falcon. It is also the most northerly, as it is rarely found south of it's breeding territories in arctic Europe, Siberia, North America, Greenland and Iceland. It varies in colour from dark grey to almost pure white. In general, the paler birds are found further to the north where their colouration camouflages them against the snowy ground.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: Gyrfalcons feed mainly on birds. Ducks, seabirds and even geese are hunted but over 95 percent of an adult's diet may consist of Ptarmigan (a small grouse). Juvenile falcons sometimes feed on mammals, including Lemmings. Most prey is caught on the wing, but is also sometimes taken from the ground. Unlike many falcons, which will only hunt over short distances before giving up, the Gyrfalcon is very persistent and will pursue prey until it is caught or manages to escape.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenland Falcon
NarNarrative: The Gyrfalcon has always been a popular bird with falconers due to it's large size and distinctive colouration. In medieval times only emperors and kings were allowed to own them, and the birds have always attracted a certain prestige. Until relatively recently there was no captive breeding and the demand for Gyrfalcons was supplied with birds captured in the wild. Prices could be very high, with wealthy falconers paying tens of thousands of pounds for a white Gyrfalcon.

It breeds around lakes and rivers in forested regions of northern Europe, including parts of northern England and Scotland.

They nest in a variety of places including hollow logs or in tree holes up to 25 metres above the ground.

NarNarrative: The Greater Bird of Paradise is native to the Aru Islands, which lie off the coast of New Guinea. In the 17th century the first of these birds was brought back to Europe by Dutch explorers. They were stuffed and had their feet cut off. Some people believed this was because the birds never needed to land on the ground, and instead floated above it in Heaven. This led to the common name for the group - Birds of Paradise.

ExhTitle: The Hancocks: Scientists in the Studio
ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Fischer's Lovebird
NarNarrative: Fischer's lovebird is native to northern Tanzania where it lives in small flocks in the woodlands and savannah grassland. Its small size and brightly coloured plumage have meant that it has become very popular in the pet trade - so much so that wild populations were greatly reduced by trappers. However a total ban on trade in Fischer's lovebird has now been implemented and wild populations are slowly recovering.

It's also a common sight on farmland and in and around towns and cities in the region. It can become very tame and is an excellent mimic of human speech. This has made it a very popular cage bird all over the world.

NarNarrative: The Little Blue penguin is the world's smallest penguin. It spends about 80% of its life at sea in the southern ocean, feeding on small fish, squid and krill. It nests in burrows on the coast of Southern Australia as well as in New Zealand and several sub-antarctic islands. They are one of the rarer penguin species, with a total breeding population that is estimated to be less than 500,000 pairs.

NarNarrative: The Grey Heron is common across most of Europe and is widespread across much of Asia and Africa. It can be seen around almost any body of water ranging from coastal salt flats and estuaries to inland lakes and rivers, marshes and even garden ponds. It nests in trees, and often forms large nesting colonies, or heronries, in summer. Most populations migrate south for the winter, but British herons are unusual in that they stay here throughout the year.

However, recent genetic analysis of the specimen has confirmed that it was in fact a Spanish Imperial Eagle.

It feeds on a variety of prey animals ranging from large insects up to game birds and rabbits.

It will also sometimes take mammals and birds. It's capable of catching and killing animals up to the size of a swan.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Spanish Imperial Eagle
NarNarrative: Spanish Imperial Eagles feed mainly on rabbits. However, they will take a variety of animals as prey depending on where they live. Birds living near water often feed on ducks and geese. This bird has been mounted with a Red Legged Partridge, another bird that is sometimes taken. The recent decline in eagle numbers has been linked to epidemics of Myxomatosis and Viral Haemorrhagic Pneumonia in the rabbit population, which has vastly reduced the food available to the eagles.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Spanish Imperial Eagle, Adalbert's Eagle
NarNarrative: There are probably fewer than 160 breeding pairs of Spanish Imperial Eagles in the world. The eagles make a nest of branches and twigs in a tree, normally over 10 metres from the ground. Branches are added to the nest throughout the breeding season, and it may be used for several years, becoming a huge structure. They normally lay two eggs, which are incubated by both parents. This bird was shot at Corral de la Citu, Spain, in 1891.
SciName: Aquila adalberti : Accipitridae : Falconiformes : Aves : Chordata

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Passenger Pigeon
NarNarrative: The Passenger pigeon was once one of the most numerous birds in the world. Flocks of millions would gather in the forests of the USA, often breaking the branches of trees due to the sheer weight of numbers. However, habitat destruction and uncontrolled hunting decimated the population until it was a fraction of its former size. By 1900 it was extinct in the wild and in 1914 a female called Martha, the last of her kind, died in Cincinnati zoo.

Introduced predators and forest clearance for agriculture and logging have had a devastating effect on the population. The New Zealand government has established a national project to help the species recover.

NarNarrative: The Ptarmigan is similar to a grouse and lives throughout the Arctic region - Iceland, Greenland and much of Scandinavia. In Britain the Ptarmigan breeds at high altitudes in the mountains of northern and western Scotland. It is well adapted to the cold mountain climate. It's feet and legs are covered with a thick layer of feathers to protect them from the cold, and in winter it's feathers become completely white so that it blends into the snow covered landscape.

It feeds exclusively on pine seeds, which it extracts from the cones using its unusual 'crossed over' bill. Its ability to withstand cold weather means that it breeds all year round and sometimes has chicks on the nest during December and January.

NarNarrative: Originally this dodo was brought to Europe by Dutch sailors during the 15th Century. It became part of the collection of John Tredescant, a famous traveler and naturalist, and in 1683 it was donated to Oxford University. During the 1700s the specimen, by then decaying, was accidentally thrown into the fire during a clean up - luckily a foot and the dodo's head were salvaged. A cast of the head was presented to the Natural History Society of Northumbria in 1841.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Pied Wagtail. Adult mounted on branch.
NarNarrative: The Pied Wagtail is a commonly encountered bird of open places that is also found in and around towns and cities. It can be seen around almost any patch of grass, including playing fields, parks and gardens and is very energetic, constantly wagging its tail and running along the ground. Birds that breed in the north of Scotland fly south to more lowland areas in the winter, but elsewhere the species stays all year round.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Greenfinch, adult in perching position.
NarNarrative: The greenfinch is a seed eating bird and can always be found in forested areas, particularly around conifers. The trend for planting conifers in many gardens has been a great advantage for the Greenfinch, which can now be found in many suburban areas and urban parks, where it often perches high up in tall trees.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Goldfinch.
NarNarrative: The Goldfinch is common throughout Europe and feeds mainly on small seeds. It often lives in areas such as orchards where there is lots of open space between trees where tall weeds like teasel and thistles - it's preferred food - can grow. It is one of the most agile of all the finches, using it's feet to maintain its balance as it pulls seeds out of thistle heads, and nipping off the unwanted husks with its beak.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Chaffinch. Adult.
NarNarrative: The Chaffinch is a small finch that is found in forests throughout Europe, although in many places it has become a common garden bird. It has a very broad diet, eating seeds, fruit, insects and invertebrates. In Britain birds are very resident, and rarely move more than 5km away from where they hatched throughout their lives. Elsewhere in Europe, birds tend to be more migratory - many birds from Scandinavia fly to Britain during the winter.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Robin
NarNarrative: The robin is one of the most familiar garden birds in Britain, and is traditionally associated with Christmas, perhaps due to it's bright red colouring. The robin has always had a place in European Folklore. It was once believed that anyone who harmed a robin would struck down by lightning or cursed by witches.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of two adult Grey Wagtails on branch. One juvenile/winter (?).
NarNarrative: The Grey Wagtail is a resident throughout the British Isles, and breeds alongside fast flowing upland streams. It is a common sight beside water in many northern areas in the summer, and moves down into more lowland areas in the winter, again often seen on or near water. It has the longest tail of all of the wagtails, and flicks it up and down almost incessantly as it walks.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of an adult Yellow Wagtail on branch.
NarNarrative: The Yellow Wagtail is an unmistakable bird which is a summer visitor to eastern and southern parts of the British Isles. It is a small wagtail which nests in meadows and farm fields, often following herds of cattle to catch the insects that they have disturbed. The birds which nest in Britain belong to one of at least 14 distinct races of this species which are found in different regions of Europe and Asia.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mounted of a Long-tailed Tit
NarNarrative: The Long Tailed Tit is common throughout the British Isles except for the far north and west of Scotland. It prefers woodlands but will nest in hedgerows and anywhere where there is dense cover so that it can build a nest. It is easily identified due to it's very tail, which is longer than it's body. It is most often seen moving through the treetops in small flocks, searching for insects and seeds.
SciName: Aegithalos caudatus : Aegithalidae : Passeriformes : Aves : Chordata

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of an adult Eurasian Common Cuckoo mounted on branch. Display posture (?).
NarNarrative: The Common Cuckoo is native to most of Europe and Asia, from Spain to Japan. It is a summer migrant over much of this area, with European birds flying south to spend the winter in Africa. The Cuckoo is a brood parasite, which means that it lays its eggs in the nests of other birds. A female cuckoo always lays her eggs in a nest belonging to the same species as the bird which raised her.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of Blue Tit.
NarNarrative: The Blue Tit is one of the most familiar garden birds in the UK. It is found throughout Britain apart from the far north. Although it is a woodland bird, it has become adapted to living in suburban areas. It readily visits bird tables, especially in winter. Blue tits are also known for their habit of tearing open milk bottles to get at the contents. In some areas they have even been seen following milk floats on their daily rounds.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Great Tit
NarNarrative: The Great Tit is a woodland bird which has readily adapted to man-made habitats to become a familiar garden visitor. It can be quite aggressive at a bird table, fighting off smaller birds. In winter it joins with blue tits and other birds and forms flocks which visit gardens and the countryside for food. It feeds on a variety of insects, seeds and nuts.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Coal Tit
NarNarrative: The Coal Tit is a small bird that is found all over the UK. It is less colourful than the other British tit species and prefers woodland with lots of birch trees and conifers. It is a common visitor to gardens, where it prefers peanut feeders. In the autumn Coal Tits will often take food and store it for the harsh winter months.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of an Owl.
NarNarrative: This bird was shot near Whitburn in October, 1848 and was acquired for the museum by John Hancock. It is one of about 60 that have been recorded in Britain over the last two centuries. Tengmalm's Owl is native to most of Europe, Asia and northern North America, and will travel long distances to find food. Birds which reach this country are most often seen on the eastern coast and have normally been blown across the North Sea from Scandinavia.
LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Sunderland, Whitburn

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Swallow in perching posture.
NarNarrative: The Swallow belongs to a family of small birds that spend most of their time in the air and only occasionally land on the ground. Swallows build a hard nest out of mud, often in a barn or around buildings, and may return to the same nest for many years. They migrate over extremely long distances - travelling from Europe and Russia in early autumn each year to southern Africa and making the return journey the following spring.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a House Martin in flight posture.
NarNarrative: House martins look similar to swallows, but are smaller and more agile in the air, flying higher and faster. Originally, they would have nested in more rocky, mountainous environments to the swallow. However, as their name suggests, they have been quick to take advantage of the growth in urban areas. Where there are plenty of insects, house martins will build their mud nests, even in housing estates or city centres, where they nest on walls and under window ledges.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Snipe. Bill slightly open.
NarNarrative: The Snipe, like many waders, is a bird of marshes and wetlands and normally lives hidden in dense undergrowth feeding on insects and worms. Snipe are normally very secretive and will fly away if disturbed - they have many predators including foxes and birds of prey. If the female is nesting and has small chicks when she is disturbed, she will sometimes pick them up in her long beak and carry them to safety.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Redshank
NarNarrative: The redshank is native to much of Europe and Asia, and is found almost anywhere near water. In Britain, it is probably best known as a shore bird, and can often be seen feeding on the tide line and in rock pools. During the summer the Redshank can also be seen nesting in upland areas around the country. Britain supports an important breeding population of Redshank - over 30,000 pairs.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mounted adult. Head lowered in feeding posture.
NarNarrative: The Curlew is the largest and one of the most familiar wading birds in Britain, its long curved bill making it instantly recognisable. It can often be seen feeding in coastal areas during the winter, or at its breeding grounds in moorland areas during the spring and summer. Curlews are often heard rather than seen, as they have a very distinctive, bubbling song.

Mount of a Little Ringed Plover
NarNarrative:
Camouflage

,

Here is the Little Ringed Plover. It is a very small bird that can be found living in England. It nests on shale and gravel covered ground, leaving their nests quite exposed. This makes it difficult for the bird to keep her eggs safe. How do you think she does this? The eggs are perfectly camouflaged to match the nest and its surroundings which make them very hard to see

,

Little Ringed Plover

,

The plover did not live in the UK until around World War II. Each year it arrives in March and will stay until June or July.

,

Little Ringed Plover Eggs

,

These eggs would be hidden in the nest. Even if the plover wasn't there, they would still be protected.

NarNarrative: Predation by introduced mongooses and human exploitation caused the extinction or near-extinction of this very poorly known seabird of the forested mountains of eastern Jamaica. When first reported in 1789 it was apparently plentiful but by the late 19th century the species was considered to be almost extinct. It was nocturnal, flying out to sea each evening to feed and returning before dawn. This bird was collected in 1866 and is one of only 22 specimens known to exist.

ColPhysicalDescription: Skeleton mounted of a Gyrfalcon
NarNarrative: This is the skeleton of a male bird, an Iceland Falcon, which is the Iceland varety of the Gyr Falcon. It may have come from one of the mounted specimens of Iceland Falcons that John Hancock displayed at the Crystal Palace Great Exhibition of 1851, which are now part of the Hancock collection. These falcons hunt along rocky open country, coastline and islands. They prey on smaller birds by dropping onto them very fast from a great height. Gyr Falcons from Iceland are slightly darker than the Greenland race. See also NEWHM:S0114

ColPhysicalDescription: Skeleton mounted of a Gyrfalcon
NarNarrative: This is the skeleton of a female Iceland Falcon. John Hancock had several specimens of this subspecies from Norway and Iceland. He mounted the skins in various displays, and in 1884 presented them, with the rest of his collection, to the Natural History Society to display in their newly built museum, now named after him and his brother. In Gyr Falcons the plumage of the sexes is very similar, although the females are slightly larger than the males. This is noticeable in their skeletons.

Skeleton missing right tarso-metatarsus and parts of one wing of a Shag
NarNarrative: The Shag's pelvis, or hip bone is long and slender, which is typical of swimming birds. In this side view the front of the bird is on the left and you are looking at the left side pelvic bone with the vertebral column runnning along behind it, between the two pelvic bones. You can see some vertebrae showing beneath them on the far left. There are two holes in the side of each pelvic bone and the small round one is at the place where the left leg is attached. The tail bones are missing, but they would be at the top right (in the picture) of the pelvic bone, where the vertebral column reaches the lower end of the pelvis.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Kakapo
NarNarrative: The kakapo is a large nocturnal parrot. It lives on the ground and feeds on grasses and seeds. This strange bird was once common in New Zealand, but humans and introduced predators greatly reduced the population and there are now only 86 birds left, living on a few small offshore islands. A breeding programme is underway to try to save them from extinction.
SciName: Strigops habroptilus : Strigopidae : Psittaciformes : Aves : Chordata

ExhTitle: The Hancocks: Scientists in the Studio
ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Huia, extinct species.
Mount of a Kokako (Blue-wattled Crow)
NarNarrative: The kokako is one of the rare New Zealand wattlebirds. There are two sub-species - one from North Island and one from South Island. This bird's blue wattles show that it is from North Island. The birds from South Island have orange wattles, but sadly the South Island subspecies is believed to be extinct. The kokako lives is dense forests and is famous for its very loud song, which can carry for miles across the forest.
ComName_tab: Kokako, North Island Kokako, Blue-wattled Crow
SciName: Callaeas cinerea wilsoni : Callaeidae : Pesseriformes : Aves : Chordata

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Little Spotted Kiwi
NarNarrative: This is one of the rarest species of kiwi. It's nocturnal, and the only bird known to have nostrils at the very end of it's bill. It literally sniffs out food. Kiwis mate for life, and can live for up to 30 years. About 1000 survive on Kapiti island. Smaller populations exist on a few other small islands. Introduced predators are the biggest killer. Stoats and cats kill most chicks before they're six months old. Dogs often kill the adults.
ComName_tab: Little Spotted Kiwi, Little Grey Kiwi, Kiwi
SciName: Apteryx owenii : Apterygidae : Apterygiformes : Aves : Chordata
LocalSum: New Zealand, South Island, East Coast

ExhTitle: Endless Forms: Charles Darwin, Natural Science and the Visual Arts, Endless Forms: Charles Darwin, Natural Science and the Visual Arts
ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Gyrfalcon. Called 'Struggle with the Quarry', the mount shows a gyrfalcon attacking a grey heron. The mount was prepared by John Hancock and was one of the pieces displayed in the Great Exhibition in 1851
NarNarrative:
35.

,

The Struggle With The Quarry, 1851    

,

 

,

The Struggle With The Quarry, by John Hancock, is one of his most famous works of taxidermy. Hancock is considered the father of modern taxidermy due to his revolutionary style. He used the animals to create dramatic and realistic scenes. Here, Hancock has captured the life and death struggle of two birds, a falcon and a heron. This was a radical departure from traditional forms of taxidermy. The scale and drama of this work impressed visitors to the Great Exhibition at the Crystal Palace in London in 1851.

,

 

,

John and his brother Albany were prominent members of the Natural History Society of Northumbria and played a key role in establishing its museum at Barras Bridge in Newcastle. After their deaths, the museum was renamed the Hancock Museum in their honour, and is today known as the Great North Museum: Hancock.

,

 

,

By John Hancock (1808 -1890)

,

 

,

On display at the Great North Museum are other examples of mounts by John Hancock. To see this object, book a behind-the-scenes tour of the Resource Centre. For more information, call the museum on 0191 222 6765 or email info@greatnorthmuseum.org.uk

,

 

,

Website www.greatnorthmuseum.org.uk

NarNarrative: The Golden Eagle is one of the most widespread of European Eagles, occurring in mountainous areas over most of the continent. In Britain, eagles breed in the mountains of Scotland. In recent years several pairs have attempted to breed further south, and a single breeding pair has nested at Haweswater in the Lake District for the last 30 years. The birds prefer mountainous areas, nesting on cliffs, but will nest in large trees in flat countries, like Denmark.

Mount of a Waxwing
NarNarrative: The Waxwing lives in the conifer forests of northern Scandinavia, where it feeds mainly on berries and fruit. In good years, there are lots of berries and large numbers of chicks are raised successfully. However, food soon becomes scarce and flocks of birds are forced to 'irupt' from Scandinavia in search of food. They reach many parts of Europe on these winter trips, often ending up in Britain where the berries of garden bushes are a favourite food.

Mount of a Great Grey Shrike
Mount of a Great Grey Shrike
NarNarrative: The Great Grey Shrike is a predatory bird that feeds on large insects, small birds and rodents. They don't have sharp talons, but instead carry their unfortunate prey to a nearby bush and impale it on a sharp thorn or twig to kill it. This rather gruesome habit has given the Great Grey Shrike the colloquial name 'Butcher Bird'. It's an uncommon visitor to Britain. A few of these birds spend the winter in parts of the south.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Steppe Grey Shrike
Mount of a Lesser Grey Shrike
NarNarrative: The Lesser Grey Shrike is a small shrike that is native to areas of Greece, Turkey and the Balkans as well as parts of Central Asia. It lives in areas with scattered trees, often nesting in vineyards and orchards. Birds are occasionally seen in Britain, where they are normally found on the east coast during spring and autumn - these are birds which have become lost whilst on migration.

Mount of a Gannet
NarNarrative: The Gannet is the largest seabird native to Britain. It's a fast and powerful flyer and feeds by diving vertically into the water at great speed. Gannets are well equipped for these spectacular plunges. Unlike most birds, they have binocular vision - both eyes face forwards. They also have a system of air cells under the skin of their neck and shoulders. As the gannet dives these air cells are inflated to cushion its body as it strikes the water.

It is unusual in that, unlike most game birds, it spends most of its time high up in the canopy, only flying across gaps between the trees. It has a varied diet of seeds, berries and small insects and is known for its distinctive call

Mount of a Queen Victoria's Riflebird
NarNarrative: The Queen Victoria's Riflebird is a Bird of Paradise native to the tropical rainforests of Australasia. In the breeding season the male attracts females with an elaborate display which shows off his dramatic plumage. Generally, he will stand upright and raise his wings above his head. This shows off his iridescent dark green and purple feathers as he sways from side to side. If the female is attracted he encircles her in his wings and taps her with them.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a King Bird of Paradise
NarNarrative: The king Bird of Paradise is one of the smallest species in this group - about the size of a starling. It's a fairly widespread species that is native to much of lowland Papua New Guinea. Its distinctive tail streamers carry two dark green spiral plumes, which are commonly used in headdresses by the indigenous people. The plumes are traded right across the island, which means that they are often found a long way away from the bird's normal habitat.

ColPhysicalDescription: Mount of a Great Bustard
Mount of a Great Bustard
NarNarrative: The Great Bustard is the largest species of bird in Europe. They can fly, but usually run away when threatened. Unfortunately, they have been hunted to extinction in many places. The last ones in Britain were killed in the 1830s.

NarNarrative: The Cuckoo is a brood parasite. This means that it lays it's eggs in the nests of other birds. The cuckoo lays a single egg in each 'foster' nest. This egg hatches very quickly, and the newly hatched cuckoo then pushes any other eggs or chicks out of the nest. The Cuckoo normally grows to be much larger than its foster parents. This Tree pipit's nest with a cuckoo egg (upper right) was collected in Axwell Park, Gateshead in 1885.
LocalSum: UK, England, Tyne and Wear (NE England), Burnhope, Axwell Park

ColPhysicalDescription: Bird eggs and nest of a Robin. 6cl.
NarNarrative: This Robin's nest with a cuckoo egg (top) was collected at Birtley Fell in 1882. A female Cuckoo will normally lay it's eggs in a nest belonging to the same species as her own host parents, so the bird that laid this egg was probably raised by Robins. The Cuckoo's eggs have evolved to closely match the colour and pattern of its hosts eggs. Cuckoos that favour different host species will have eggs that look very different to each other.
LocalSum: UK, England, Co. Durham (NE England), Birtley Fell

NarNarrative: This is a plaster model of Great Auk's egg. This was a large flightless seabird that went extinct during the late 1840s. At that time, specimens of the rare bird and it's eggs were in great demand with collectors. John Hancock, who made this model, owned an egg, but supplemented his collection by making copies of eggs that belonged to other collectors. This is a model of an egg that belonged to J. P Wilmot. It was made in 1856.

NarNarrative: The Gentoo penguin is one of the smaller species of Penguin. It has a broad distribution throughout the southern polar region, nesting in large colonies on the Falklands, Iles Keregulen in the Southern Ocean and various Sub-Antarctic island territories of Australia and New Zealand. Unlike many penguin species it is largely sedentary, staying in the same place all year round. It feeds mainly on squid and krill.
